Habitat. Wet to semiarid habitats, including rainforests, wet and dry sclerophyll forests, Melaleuca ( Myrtaceae ) woodlands, waterways lined with river red gum ( Eucalyptus camaldulensis, Myrtaceae ), woodlands, and Acacia ( Fabaceae ) shrublands from sea level up to elevations of ¢. 1240 m (in
Victoria
). Gould’s Long-eared Bat is confined to more humid, temperate regions in Western Australia . It seems to need dense understories in tall forests to establish roosts.
